[{"sha":"b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20","author":{"name":"Håkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Add pre-load CPU feature guard check

Compile a small shared library that performs an x86 CPU feature guard
check that compares the features enabled during compile-time with the
features available at run-time (using the `CPUID` instruction). This
comparison is done during static initialization and the process is
aborted with an error message if we have compiled with a feature that is
not supported by the current CPU.

Such a check is already performed during static initialization of the
library `libtensorflow_framework.so.2`, but since this library performs
many actions during initialization, there is a high risk of triggering
an illegal instruction before we reach the check, depending on the
(undefined) static initialization order.

Because of this we compile a separate shared library that we load as a
self-check before loading `_pywrap_tensorflow_internal.so`.

We also change to use `<iostream>` for printing in case of a failed
check, as use of the logging framework might itself trigger an
illegal instruction (it did in my testing).

Tested by attempting to use a wheel built with AVX-512 on an AMD CPU:

Before:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
Illegal instruction
```

After:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
The TensorFlow library was compiled to use AVX512F instructions, but these aren't available on your machine.
Aborted

Previously, we would reject saving custom ops by default and force the user
to whitelist each custom namespace in their call to save.  This made it tricky
for creators of custom ops to migrate to using namespaces; even if their
downstream users were already using the custom ops without issue, migrating
to namespaces would force the users to change their save code to explicitly
whitelist the ops.

[{"sha":"ca1c7b8d740d79fd397658240e34f3d61cf574ed","author":{"name":"George Karpenkov","email":"bbf3fb1cea1ba929a95f09c9e20513124012c8d3@google.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Do not MOF-fuse more than N (N=8) unnested reductions into a single fusion

Larger fusions lead to spilling.

Could be related to parallel reduction grouping in
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/42717, but I could still see
spilling even if only 1 parallel group is observed.

At this point it looks like a ptxas register allocation issue, since ptxas
should realize that all reductions in a MOF are alive at different time.

Note that we already have a similar constraint for column reductions, since we
have a shared memory budget, and we run out of shared memory budget for column
reduction much faster.

MoveEndpointInModule.

CanChainFrom allows the linking of move statements of the same address,
which means the prior destination address must equal the following
source address. If the destination and source addresses are of different
types, they must be covered by NestedWithin rather than CanChainFrom.

NestedWithin checks if the destination contains the source address. Any

[{"sha":"858825431c21ebdde772e9e9d9b91e11786c2cb6","author":{"name":"Jean-Baptiste Lespiau","email":"d3229a97a8a1a3969929b7309247ec1d345f5156@google.com"},"message":"Make it possible to return a C++ `ShardedDeviceArray`.

This **will** be a **breaking** change, as pxla.ShardedDeviceArray constructor won't be valid anymore:
- for the next Jax release
- on the condition _USE_EXPERIMENTAL_CPP_SDA is switch to `_xla_extension_version > xx` and with the associated jaxlib release.

I am already adding the impact for the users in the CHANGELOG, we can still move it to the next version depending on when it's shipped.

Similarly to JAX.jit, for which we have a C++ `DeviceArray` and a Python `_DeviceArray`, we will introduce 2 objects for ShardedDeviceArray, with the Python object only for JAX extensions not compatible with the C++ object (e.g. Cloud TPU).

- Add `make_sharded_device_array` to be used within JAX and for hackers that need to construct SDA objects.
- Make sure the C++ object is valid by
  (a) extending `DeviceArrayBase` (done in Python), as it brings a bunch of methods and enable `isinstance(x, DeviceArray)`
  (b) Adding the same methods as the Python SDA.

NOTE: mypy has troubled with the " -> pxla.ShardedDeviceArray` function return type annotation, I had to remove 2.

[{"sha":"a4b53af710f1e1dc41279e2de7cf6ec8b092f28b","author":{"name":"Reed Wanderman-Milne","email":"75734eae9db3e4fb4d6c671d22722b468d1a389b@google.com"},"message":"Raise error if random ops used with determinism without seed.

This change is described in the determinism RFC: https://github.com/tensorflow/community/blob/master/rfcs/20210119-determinism.md#random-ops.

There are two minor changes from the RFC:

1. Instead of raising a FailedPreconditionError, as the RFC specifies, a RuntimeError is raised from Python and an InvalidArgument error is raised from C++. The reason for the RuntimeError is that typically only built-in Python errors are raised in TF Python code. The reason for the InvalidArgument error is that C++ ops take "seed" attributes, and so if they are set to zero (meaning to choose them nondeterministically), it means the "seed" arguments are invalid.

2. tf.compat.v1.get_seed raises a RuntimeError if no seed is set and determinism is enabled. This is the most natural place to put the error, and it means custom random ops with Python ops will also raise errors when necessary.
